  <bioghist audience="internal" id="aspace_a2">
    <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
<p>The papers consist of materials relating to three generations of the Pierce family of Cornwall, principally Joshua Pierce (ca.1702-1794) and his son Seth Pierce (1742-1833), but also several of Joshua’s grandchildren. . Originally from Pembroke, Massachusetts, the Pierce family removed to Cornwall in 1748. Joshua Pierce and his descendants were particularly influential in community military and religious matters.</p>  </bioghist>
  <scopecontent audience="internal" id="aspace_a3">
    <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
<p>Joshua Pierce’s deeds reveal the family’s vast property holdings first in eastern Massachusetts, and later in Cornwall. The Revolutionary War records of Seth Pierce deal primarily with the purchases of weapons and food, as well as troop movements in western Connecticut. The deeds of Seth Pierce show his steady accumulation of land in Cornwall during and after the war, especially in the Great Hollow. Seth Pierce’s receipts reveal transactions with individuals such as Ebenezer Sherwood, Hannah Griffis, Isaac Swift, Benjamin Conkling, Eleanor Johnson, Daniel Merritt, Isaac Talman, Josiah Sanford, Ethel North, Ozias Buell, and Dr. Ebenezer North. Seth Pierce’s influence in local military and religious matters is reflected in his accounts with both General Heman Swift and the First Ecclesiastical Society. The deeds of Seth Pierce’s son, “Major” Seth II, similarly illustrate a steady accumulation of land in Cornwall, especially from the Gold family in Cornwall Plains.</p>  </scopecontent>
